# Customer Segmentation via Clustering Algorithms

Comparative analysis of four unsupervised learning methods applied to credit card customer data, with automated hyperparameter selection and fair cross-algorithm evaluation.

## Overview

**Dataset:** [Credit Card Customer Data](https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/arjunbhasin2013/ccdata) — 8,950 customers, 17 behavioral features  
**Goal:** Identify distinct customer segments to support product targeting and business decision-making

## Methods

| Algorithm | Strengths |
|-----------|-----------|
| K-Means | Scalable, interpretable, best overall metric scores |
| Agglomerative | Hierarchical structure via dendrogram, validates k choice |
| DBSCAN | Explicit noise/outlier detection |
| OPTICS | Handles variable-density clusters, reachability plot |

## Key Design Decisions

- **Automated hyperparameter selection** — KneeLocator detects optimal k (Elbow method) and eps (K-distance graph) without manual tuning
- **Fair evaluation** — DBSCAN and OPTICS noise points are reassigned to the nearest cluster centroid before metric computation, so all four algorithms are scored on 100% of data
- **PCA scoped to visualization only** — clustering and all metrics run on the full 17-dimensional feature space; 2D PCA projections are used solely for plots
- **Graceful degradation** — if DBSCAN collapses to a single cluster (a known failure mode on high-dimensional standardized data), metrics are skipped with a clear warning instead of producing invalid scores

## Evaluation Metrics

- Silhouette Score (higher = better)
- Davies-Bouldin Index (lower = better)  
- Calinski-Harabasz Index (higher = better)

## Results

K-Means (k=4) achieves the best scores across all three metrics and is recommended as the production baseline. Four interpretable customer segments were identified:

| Cluster | Profile |
|---------|---------|
| 0 | Low-activity — low balance, low purchases |
| 1 | High one-off spenders — high total purchases |
| 2 | Cash-advance heavy users — high advance frequency |
| 3 | Full payers — low balance, high payment ratio |

